A: You can use the following code to save the changes made to jTable:
// Get the data from the jTable
Object[][] data = jTable.getModel().getDataVector();

// Create a StringBuilder to store the data
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

// Loop through the data and append it to the StringBuilder
for (int i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < data[i].length; j++) {
        sb.append(data[i][j]);
        if (j < data[i].length - 1) {
            sb.append(",");
        }
    }
    sb.append("\n");
}

// Write the data to a file
try {
    FileWriter writer = new FileWriter("data.txt");
    writer.write(sb.toString());
    writer.close();
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}

This code will get the data from the jTable, store it in a StringBuilder, and then write the data to a file called "data.txt". You can modify the code to save the data in a different format or to a different file.
